<div id="main">
  <h1 id="title">Pixel Art</h1>
  <div>A form of digital art originating from classic video games</div>
  <div id="img-div">
    <img id="image" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/71/The_Gunk_699px.png" alt="">
    <div id="img-caption">Pixel art image drawn by Lucas V. Barbosa, titled "The Gunk".
    </div>
  </div>
  <div id="tribute-info">
      <p>Pixel art began in arcades and 8-bit consoles, with titles like Space Invaders (1978) and The Legend of Zelda (1986).</p>
        <p>For some of us, this is how we first experiended video games. The 8-bit and 16-bit styles often carries a strong sense of nostalgia.</p>
      <p>Today, many indie games make incredible use of pixel art, such as Stardew Valley and Hyper Light Drifter.</p>
      <ul>
      <li>In order to get around color palette limitations, anti-aliasing and dithering techniques are used to simulate a broader range of colors.
      <li>Cross-stitch, mosaic and beadwork share similarities with pixel art</li>
      <li>The term pixel art was first published by Adele Goldberg and Robert Flegal in 1982</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>If you want to learn more about pixel art, follow this link to the <a id="tribute-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel_art" target="_blank">Wikipedia Entry</a>.</h3>
  </div>
</div>
